# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bimodal-bilingualism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] 'alphabet') is a writing system in which only consonants are represented by letter signs, leaving the vowels to be inferred by the reader (unless represented otherwise, such as by diacritics).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] This contrasts with alphabets that provide graphemes for both consonants and vowels.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The term was introduced in 1990 by Peter T.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Other terms for the same concept include **partial phonemic script**, **segmentally linear defective phonographic script**, **consonantary**, **consonant writing**, and **consonantal alphabet**.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] According to the formulations of Peter T.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Daniels, abjads differ from alphabets in that only consonants, not vowels, are represented among the basic graphemes.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Abjads differ from abugidas, another category defined by Daniels, in that in abjads, the vowel sound is *implied* by phonology, and where vowel marks exist for the system, such as niqqud for Hebrew and ḥarakāt for Arabic, their use is optional and not the dominant (or literate) form.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Abugidas mark all vowels (other than the "inherent" vowel) with a diacritic, a minor attachment to the letter, a standalone grapheme, or (in Canadian Aboriginal syllabics) by rotation of the letter.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Some abugidas use a special symbol to *suppress* the inherent vowel so that the consonant alone can be properly represented.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] In a syllabary, a grapheme denotes a complete syllable, that is, either a lone vowel sound or a combination of a vowel sound with one or more consonant sounds.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The contrast of abjad versus alphabet has been rejected by other scholars because *abjad* is also used as a term for the Arabic numeral system.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Also, it may be taken as suggesting that consonantal alphabets, in contrast to e.g. the Greek alphabet, were not yet true alphabets.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Florian Coulmas, a critic of Daniels and of the abjad terminology, argues that this terminology can confuse alphabets with "transcription systems", and that there is no reason to relegate the Hebrew, Aramaic or Phoenician alphabets to second-class status as an "incomplete alphabet".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] However, Daniels's terminology has found acceptance in the linguistic community.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script represents the earliest-known example of alphabetic writing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script is thought to represent, or at least indicate the existence of, an early ancestor of the many later Semitic consonantal scripts which continued to develop over time into more abstract, less visually representational forms, including the Phoenician abjad.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The Phoenician abjad was a radical simplification of phonetic writing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Unlike other scripts, such as Mesopotamian cuneiform (logographic and syllabic) and Egyptian hieroglyphs (logographic and consonantal), the Phoenician abjad consisted of only a few dozen symbols.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] During these exchanges, the Phoenician script gave rise to a number of new writing systems, including the widely used Aramaic abjad and the Greek alphabet.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The Greek alphabet was later developed into several alphabets, including Etruscan, Coptic, Cyrillic, and Latin (via Etruscan), while Aramaic became the ancestor of many abjads and abugidas of Asia, particularly in and around India, Southeast Asia, and Oceania.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Impure abjads have characters for some vowels, optional vowel diacritics, or both.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The term pure abjad refers to scripts entirely lacking in vowel indicators.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] This practice was at first rare and limited in scope but became increasingly common and more developed in later times.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] In the 9th century BC the Greeks adapted the Phoenician script for use in their own language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The phonetic structure of the Greek language created too many ambiguities when vowels went unrepresented, so the script was modified.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] They did not need letters for the guttural sounds represented by *aleph*, *he*, *heth* or *ayin*, so these symbols were assigned vocalic values.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The letters *waw* and *yod* were also adapted into vowel signs; along with *he*, these were already used as *matres lectionis* in Phoenician.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Abugidas developed along a slightly different route.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The basic consonantal symbol was considered to have an inherent "a" vowel sound.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Hooks or short lines attached to various parts of the basic letter modify the vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] In this way, the South Arabian abjad evolved into the Geʽez script of Ethiopia between the 5th century BC and the 5th century AD.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] Similarly, the Brāhmī abugida of the Indian subcontinent developed around the 3rd century BC (from the Aramaic abjad, it has been hypothesized).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The abjad form of writing is well-adapted to the morphological structure of the Semitic languages it was developed to write.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] This is because words in Semitic languages are formed from a root consisting of (usually) three consonants, the vowels being used to indicate inflectional or derived forms.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] In most cases, the absence of full glyphs for vowels makes the common root clearer, allowing readers to guess the meaning of unfamiliar words from familiar roots (especially in conjunction with context clues) and improving word recognition while reading for practiced readers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abjad] The Hebrew abjad has also been adapted to write Jewish languages like Ladino and Yiddish.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] This contrasts with a full alphabet, in which vowels have status equal to consonants, and with an abjad, in which vowel marking is absent, partial, or optional.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In less formal contexts, all three types of script may be termed "alphabets".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The terms also contrast them with a syllabary, in which a single symbol denotes the combination of a consonant and a vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Related concepts were introduced independently in 1948 by James Germain Février (using the term *néosyllabisme*) and David Diringer (using the term *semisyllabary*), and in 1959 by Fred Householder (introducing the term *pseudo-alphabet*).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Ethiopic term "abugida" was chosen as a designation for the concept in 1990 by Peter T.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Faber suggested "segmentally coded syllabically linear phonographic script"; William O.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Bright used the term *alphasyllabary*; and Gnanadesikan and Rimzhim, Katz, & Fowler suggested *aksara* or *āksharik*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Abugidas include the extensive Brahmic family of scripts of Tibet and South and Southeast Asia; Semitic Ethiopic scripts; and Canadian Aboriginal syllabics.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] As in syllabaries, the writing system's units may consist of representations of both syllables and consonants.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] For scripts of the Brahmic family, the term *akshara* is used for the units.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In several languages of Ethiopia and Eritrea, *abugida* traditionally meant letters of the Ethiopic or Geʽez script in which many of these languages are written.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Geʽez script is one of several segmental writing systems; others include Indic/Brahmic scripts and Canadian Aboriginal Syllabics.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The word *abugida* derives from the letters *'ä, bu, gi,* and *da*, in much the same way that *abecedary* derives from the Latin letters *a be ce de*, *abjad* derives from the Arabic *a b j d*, and *alphabet* derives from the two first letters in the Greek alphabet, *alpha* and *beta*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] *Abugida* as a term in linguistics was proposed by Peter T.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Daniels in his 1990 typology of writing systems.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] As Daniels used the word, an abugida contrasts with a syllabary, where letters with shared consonant or vowel sounds have no particular resemblance.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Furthermore, an abugida contrasts with an alphabet proper, where independent letters denote consonants and vowels.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The term *alphasyllabary* was suggested for the Indic scripts in 1997 by William O.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The formal definitions given by Daniels and Bright for abugida and alphasyllabary differ; some writing systems are abugidas but not alphasyllabaries, and some are alphasyllabaries but not abugidas.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] An abugida is defined as "a type of writing system whose basic characters denote consonants followed by a particular vowel, and in which diacritics denote other vowels".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] An alphasyllabary is defined as "a type of writing system in which the vowels are denoted by subsidiary symbols, not all of which occur in a linear order (with relation to the consonant symbols) that is congruent with their temporal order in speech".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Bright did not require that an alphabet explicitly represent all vowels. ʼPhags-pa is an example of an abugida because it has an inherent vowel, but it is not an alphasyllabary because its vowels are written in linear order.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The fundamental principles of an abugida apply to words made up of consonant-vowel (CV) syllables.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The syllables are written as letters in a straight line, where each syllable is either a letter that represents the sound of a consonant and its inherent vowel or a letter modified to indicate the vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Letters can be modified either by means of diacritics or by changes in the form of the letter itself.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] If all modifications are by diacritics and all diacritics follow the direction of the writing of the letters, the abugida is not an alphasyllabary.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] But most languages have words that are more complicated than a sequence of CV syllables, even ignoring tone.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The first complication is syllables that consist of just a vowel (V).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In some languages, a zero consonant letter is used as though every syllable began with a consonant.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In others, each vowel has a separate letter that is used for each syllable consisting of just the vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] These are known as *independent vowels* and are found in most Indic scripts.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] They may be quite different from the corresponding diacritics, known as *dependent vowels*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] As a result of the spread of writing systems, independent vowels may be used to represent syllables beginning with a glottal stop, even for non-initial syllables.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The next two complications are consonant clusters before a vowel (CCV) and syllables ending in a consonant (CVC).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The simplest solution, which is not always available, is to break with the principle of writing words as a sequence of syllables and use a letter representing just a consonant (C).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In a true abugida, the lack of distinctive vowel marking of the letter may result from the diachronic loss of the inherent vowel, e.g. by syncope and apocope in Hindi.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] When not separating syllables containing consonant clusters (CCV) into C + CV, these syllables are often written by combining the two consonants.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In Indic scripts, the earliest method was simply to arrange them vertically, writing the second consonant of the cluster below the first.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The two consonants may also merge as conjunct consonant letters, where two or more letters are graphically joined in a ligature, or otherwise change their shapes.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Rarely, one of the consonants may be replaced by a gemination mark, e.g. the Gurmukhi *addak*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] When arranged vertically, as in Burmese or Khmer, they are said to be "stacked".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Often there has been a change to writing the two consonants side by side.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In the latter case, this combination may be indicated by a diacritic on one of the consonants or a change in the form of one of the consonants, e.g. the half forms of Devanagari.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Generally, the reading order of stacked consonants is top to bottom, or the general reading order of the script, but sometimes the reading order is reversed.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The division of a word into syllables for the purposes of writing does not always accord with the language's natural phonetics.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] CC or CCVC) are handled by combining the various techniques above.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Lao and Tāna have dependent vowels and a zero vowel sign, but no inherent vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Indic scripts originated in India and spread to Southeast Asia, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan, Tibet, Mongolia, and Russia.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] All surviving Indic scripts are descendants of the Brahmi alphabet.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The primary division is between North Indic scripts, used in Northern India, Nepal, Tibet, Bhutan, Mongolia, and Russia, and Southern Indic scripts, used in South India, Sri Lanka and Southeast Asia.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] South Indic letter forms are more rounded than North Indic forms, though Odia, Golmol and Litumol are rounded.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Most North Indic scripts' full letters incorporate a horizontal line at the top, except in Gujarati and Odia; South Indic scripts do not.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Indic scripts indicate vowels through dependent vowel signs (diacritics) around the consonants, often including a sign that explicitly indicates the lack of a vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] If a consonant has no vowel sign, this indicates a default vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Vowel diacritics may appear above, below, to the left of, to the right of, or around the consonant.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The most widely used Indic script is Devanagari, shared by Hindi, Bihari, Marathi, Konkani, Nepali, and often Sanskrit.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] A basic letter such as क in Hindi represents a syllable with the default vowel, in this case *ka* ([kə]).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In some languages, including Hindi, it becomes a final closing consonant at the end of a word, in this case *k*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The inherent vowel may be changed by adding vowel marks (diacritics), producing syllables such as कि *ki*, कु *ku*, के *ke*, को *ko*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In many Brahmic scripts, a syllable beginning with a cluster is treated as a single character for purposes of vowel marking, so a vowel marker like ि *-i,* falling before the character it modifies, may appear several positions before the place where it is pronounced.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] For example, the game cricket in Hindi is क्रिकेट *krikeṭ*; the diacritic for /i/ appears before the consonant cluster /kr/, not before the /r/.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] A more unusual example is seen in the Batak alphabet: the syllable *bim* is written *ba-ma-i-(virama)*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] That is, the vowel diacritic and virama are both written after the consonants for the whole syllable.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In many abugidas, there is also a diacritic to suppress the inherent vowel, yielding the bare consonant.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In Devanagari, प् is *p*, and फ् is *ph*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] This is called the *virāma* or *halantam* in Sanskrit.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] It may be used to form consonant clusters or to indicate that a consonant occurs at the end of a word.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Thus in Sanskrit, a default vowel consonant such as फ does not take on a final consonant sound.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] For writing two consonants without a vowel in between, instead of using diacritics on the first consonant to remove its vowel, another common method of special conjunct forms is used in which two or more consonant characters are merged to express a cluster, as in Devanagari's अप्फ *appha*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] (Some fonts display this as प् followed by फ, rather than forming a conjunct.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] This expedient is used by ISCII and South Asian scripts of Unicode.) Thus a closed syllable such as *phaṣ* requires two *aksharas* to write: फष् *phaṣ*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Róng script used for the Lepcha language goes further than other Indic abugidas, in that a single *akshara* can represent a closed syllable: Not only the vowel but any final consonant is indicated by a diacritic.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] For example, the syllable [sok] would be written as something like s̥̽, here with an underring representing /o/ and an overcross representing the diacritic for final /k/.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Most other Indic abugidas can indicate only a very limited set of final consonants with diacritics, such as /ŋ/ or /r/, if they can indicate any at all.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In Geʽez script, *fidels* (individual "letters" of the script) have diacritics that are fused with the consonants to the point that they must be considered modifications of the form of the letters.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Children learn each modification separately, as in a syllabary; nonetheless, the graphic similarities between syllables with the same consonant are readily apparent, unlike in a true syllabary.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Though now an abugida, the Geʽez script, until the advent of Christianity (c.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] AD 350), was what would now be termed an *abjad*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In the Geʽez script (or *fidel*), the letter's base form (also called *fidel*) may be altered.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] For example, ሀ *hä* [hə] (base form), ሁ *hu* (with a right-side diacritic that does not alter the letter), ሂ *hi* (with a subdiacritic that compresses the consonant, so it is the same height), ህ *hə* [hɨ] or [h] (where the letter is modified with a kink in the left arm).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] In the family known as Canadian Aboriginal syllabics, which was inspired by Devanagari script, vowels are indicated by changing the orientation of the syllabogram.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Each vowel has a consistent orientation; for example, Inuktitut ᐱ *pi*, ᐳ *pu*, ᐸ *pa*; ᑎ *ti*, ᑐ *tu*, ᑕ *ta*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Although a vowel is inherent in each, all rotations have equal status and none can be identified as basic.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Bare consonants are indicated either by separate diacritics or by superscript versions of the *aksharas*; there is no vowel-killer mark.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Abjads are typically written without indication of many vowels, but in some contexts, such as teaching materials or scriptures, Arabic and Hebrew are written with full indication of vowels via diacritic marks (*harakat*, *niqqud*), making them effectively alphasyllabaries.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Arabic script used for South Azerbaijani generally writes the vowel /æ/ (written as ə in North Azerbaijani) as a diacritic but all other vowels as full letters (like Kurdish and Uyghur).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] This means that when no vowel diacritics are present (most of the time), it technically has an inherent vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] But like the Phagspa and Meroitic scripts, whose status as abugidas is controversial (see below), all other vowels are written in-line.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Additionally, the practice of explicitly writing all-but-one vowel does not apply to loanwords from Arabic and Persian, so the script does not have an inherent vowel for Arabic and Persian words.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The inconsistency of its vowel notation makes it difficult to categorize.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The imperial Mongol script called Phagspa was derived from the Tibetan abugida, but all vowels are written in-line rather than as diacritics.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] However, it retains the features of having an inherent vowel /a/ and having distinct initial vowel letters.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Pahawh Hmong is a non-segmental script that indicates syllable onsets and rimes, such as consonant clusters and vowels with final consonants.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Thus it is not segmental and cannot be considered an abugida.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] It superficially resembles an abugida with the roles of consonant and vowel reversed.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Most syllables are written with two letters in the order rime–onset (typically vowel-consonant) even though they are pronounced as onset-rime (consonant-vowel), rather like the position of the /i/ vowel in Devanagari, which is written before the consonant.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Pahawh is also unusual in that, while an inherent rime /āu/ (with mid tone) is unwritten, it also has an inherent onset /k/.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] For the syllable /kau/, which requires that one of the inherent sounds be overt, it is /au/ that is written.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Thus the rime (vowel) is basic to the system.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Drawing a dividing line between abugidas and other segmental scripts can be difficult.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] For example, the Meroitic script of ancient Sudan does not indicate an inherent *a* (one symbol stood for both *m* and *ma,* for example) and is thus similar to Brahmic family of abugidas.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] But other vowels were indicated with full letters, not diacritics or modification, so the system is essentially an alphabet that does not bother to write the most common vowel.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Several systems of shorthand use diacritics for vowels, but do not have an inherent vowel, and are thus more similar to Thaana and Kurdish script than to Brahmic scripts.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Gabelsberger shorthand system and its derivatives modify the *following* consonant to represent vowels.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Pollard script, which was based on shorthand, also uses diacritics for vowels; the placements of the vowel relative to the consonant indicate tone.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Pitman shorthand uses straight strokes and quarter-circle marks in different orientations as the principal "alphabet" of consonants; vowels are shown as light and heavy dots, dashes, and other marks in one of three possible positions to indicate the various vowel-sounds.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] To increase writing speed, Pitman has rules for "vowel indication" using the positioning or choice of consonant signs so that writing vowel-marks can be dispensed with.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] As the term *alphasyllabary* suggests, abugidas have been considered an intermediate step between alphabets and syllabaries.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Historically, most abugidas appear to have evolved from abjads (vowelless alphabets).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] They contrast with syllabaries, where there is a distinct symbol for each syllable or consonant-vowel combination, and where these have no systematic similarity to each other, and typically develop directly from logographic scripts.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] Most Indian and Indochinese abugidas appear to have developed from abjads with the Kharoṣṭhī and Brāhmī scripts; the abjad in question is usually considered the Aramaic one, but while the link between Aramaic and Kharosthi is more or less undisputed, this is not so with Brahmi.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Kharosthi family does not survive today, but Brahmi's descendants include most of the modern scripts of South and Southeast Asia.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Geʽez script derives from a different abjad, the Sabean script of Yemen; the advent of vowels coincided with the introduction or adoption of Christianity about AD 350.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Ethiopic script is the elaboration of an abjad.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Cree syllabary was invented with full knowledge of the Devanagari system.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/abugida] The Meroitic script was developed from Egyptian hieroglyphs, in which various schemes of "group writing" were used to show vowels.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] Education for the deaf in Afghanistan grew out of educational efforts among Afghan refugees in Peshawar in the 1990s, making Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) an early influence on Afghan Sign Language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] The first formal school for the deaf in Afghanistan was established in Jalalabad in 1995 by SERVE Afghanistan.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] That same year, SERVE began a project to document Afghan Sign Language, and later produced a trilingual (Dari, Pashto, and English) dictionary of Afghan Sign Language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] The language derives from the Deaf-community sign language of Jalalabad, and it is not known what connection it may have, if any, with the sign languages of other cities with established deaf populations, which are principally Mazar-i-Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] Early analysis suggested some AFSL signs may have come from Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) or American Sign Language (ASL), although intensive research on this link was not undertaken at the time.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] While IPSL's influence would have been due to regional exchange, ASL could have had an influence due to its use by some SERVE teachers in its early programming.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] Fingerspelling was introduced to AFSL in the late 1990s, after SERVE educators visited the Holy Land Institute for the Deaf in Jordan.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] Thus, Jordanian Sign Language and AFSL share a fingerspelling alphabet, although AFSL also introduced some additional letters to represent letters not found in the Arabic script.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] Afghan Sign Language is primarily spoken in Jalalabad and Kabul, which have three large schools for the deaf between them.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] Smaller deaf populations who use AFSL are also found in major urban centers in the country, those being Mazar-e Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/afghan-sign-language] The majority of profoundly deaf Afghans (estimated at 30,000 in 2013) have never attended a school for the deaf.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Also addressed below: the range of language proficiencies among bimodal bilinguals, current perspectives in neurolinguistics, common misconceptions about bimodal bilingualism, and ongoing debates about terminology, educational policies, and language access.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In discussions of multilingualism in the United States, bimodal bilingualism and bimodal bilinguals have often not been mentioned or even considered.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] However, bimodal bilinguals share many of the same traits as other bilinguals (those with competency in at least two *spoken* languages), as well as differing in some interesting ways, due to the unique characteristics of the Deaf community.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Bimodal bilinguals also experience neurological benefits similar to those that unimodal bilinguals do (see Cognitive effects of bilingualism).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] American Sign Language, the predominant sign language used in the U.S., only began to be acknowledged as a natural language in the 1960s (in discussions of bimodal bilingualism in the U.S., the two languages involved are generally ASL and English).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Deaf Culture is vital to understanding this concept of bimodal bilinguals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] A substantial number of bimodal bilinguals are Children of Deaf Adults (CODA) or other hearing people who learn sign language for various reasons.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Deaf people as a group have their own sign language(s) and culture that is referred to as Deaf, but invariably live within a larger hearing culture with its own oral language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Thus, "most deaf people are bilingual to some extent in [an oral] language in some form".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Since linguists did not recognize ASL as a true language until the second half of the twentieth century, there has been very little acknowledgment of, or attention or study devoted to, the bilingual status of the American Deaf community.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Deaf people are often "still seen by many as monolingual in the majority language whereas in fact many are bilingual in that language and in sign".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Language shift "occurs when speakers in a community give up speaking their language and take up the use of another in its place".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] However, due to the *physical* fact of deafness or hearing loss, deaf people generally cannot acquire and *speak* the majority language in the same way or with the same competency that the hearing population does.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Simultaneously, Deaf people still often have a need or desire to learn some form of English in order to communicate with family members and the majority culture.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Thus, Deaf communities and individuals, in contrast to many hearing bilingual communities and individuals, will tend to "remain bilingual throughout their lives and from generation to generation".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Some bimodal bilinguals acquire both languages from an early age (a.k.a. simultaneous), while others learn one language fire and the other later on in life (sequential).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] This is dependent upon home language environment, educational language environment, and language access (regardless of sign or spoken language).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] It is not uncommon for sign language access to be delayed, limited, or no access altogether for many Deaf children especially Deaf children that are born into hearing families (which is the case 90% of the time).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Because of this, there is much variability in language exposure as well as production.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] To be defined as bilingual, an individual need not have perfect fluency or equal skill in both languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Bimodal bilinguals, like oral-language bilinguals, exhibit a wide range of language competency in their first and second languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Bimodal bilinguals show a range in their language skills.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Some are highly proficient in both modalities, whereas others heavily rely on one language over the other.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] There are other factors at play here such as age and context of exposure, education experience, community support, and how frequently the individual uses that language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Historically, assessment of bilingual children would only measure proficiency in one of their languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In more recent research, linguists and educators have identified this design flaw.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] It can be concluded that most bilingual children achieve phonological, lexical, and grammatical milestones at the same rate as monolingual children.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] This same phenomenon has been found in comparing unimodal bilinguals and bimodal bilinguals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In a study by Fish & Morford (2012), bimodal bilingual CODAs have demonstrated the same rate of success in these areas as their unimodal bilingual peers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Language proficiency among bimodal bilinguals varies widely.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Factors influencing English comprehension include age of exposure, quality of language access, educational experiences, and individual differences in literacy development.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Lipreading alone provides limited access to English phonology, as only some phonemes are visually distinguishable, but many Deaf individuals develop strong English literacy skills through multimodal exposure.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Additionally, many Deaf bilinguals who have fluency in written English choose not to speak it because of the general social unacceptability of their voices, or because they are unable to monitor factors like pitch and volume.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The simultaneous production of speech and sign is referred to as simultaneous-communication or sim-com.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Deaf or bimodal bilinguals, in their day-to-day lives, move among and between various points on the language mode continuum depending on the situation and the language competency and skills of those with whom they are interacting.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] For example, when conversing with a monolingual, all bilinguals will restrict themselves to the language of the individual with whom they are conversing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] However, when interacting with another bilingual, all bilinguals can use a mixture of the two common languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] While early aged bimodal bilinguals have more than one mode to communicate a language, they are just as susceptible as unimodal bilinguals to confusing domains and using the "wrong" language in a given situation.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Code-switching is a common phenomenon found among bilinguals; for bimodal bilinguals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Like unimodal bilinguals, bimodal bilinguals will activate, deactivate or adjust their use of each language according to their domain.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Because almost all members of the American Deaf community are to some extent bilingual in ASL and English, it is rare that a Deaf person will find themselves conversing with a person who is monolingual in ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Therefore, unless an American Deaf person is communicating with someone who is monolingual in English (the majority language), he or she can expect to be conversing in a "bilingual language mode".
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The result of this prolonged bilingual contact and mixing between a sign language and an oral language is known as contact sign.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Deaf children and their parents communicated using several modalities, such as oral-aural and visual-gestural.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The mixed use of ASL and spoken English in bilinguals is discussed in this article, and led to contact signing.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In the deaf community, contact signing is a common occurrence.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The author covered many contact sign approaches in complex layers of ASL and spoken English expressions.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Contact signing refers to forms of communication that emerge when signers and non-native signers interact, resulting in features from a signed language and a spoken language appearing together.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In the context of American Deaf communities, contact signing often occurs in interactions between ASL users and English-dominant individuals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] These forms arise from language contact rather than representing a separate language, and they vary depending on participants’ proficiencies and communication goals (Lucas, C. & Valli, C.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] *Language Contact in the American Deaf Community.* Academic Press).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Most modern neurological studies of bilingualism employ functional neuroimaging techniques to uncover the neurological underpinnings of multilingualism and how multilingualism is beneficial to the brain.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Neuroimaging and other neurological studies have demonstrated in recent years that multilingualism has a significant impact on the human brain.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Multilingualism, especially bimodal multilingualism, can help slow to process of cognitive decline in aging.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] It is thought that this is a result of the increased work load that the executive system, housed mostly in the frontal cortex, must assume in order to successfully control the use of multiple languages at once.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] This means that the cortex must be more finely tuned, which results in a "neural reserve" that then has neuroprotective benefits.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Gray matter volume (GMV) has been shown to be significantly preserved in bimodal bilinguals as compared to monolinguals in multiple brain areas, including the hippocampus, amygdala, anterior temporal lobes, and left insula.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Similarly, neuroimaging studies that have compared monolinguals, unimodal bilinguals, and bimodal bilinguals provide evidence that deaf signers exhibit brain activation in patterns different from those of hearing signers, especially in regards to the left superior temporal sulcus.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In deaf signers, activation of the superior temporal sulcus is highly lateralized to the left side during facial recognition tasks, while this lateralization was not present in hearing, bimodal signers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Bilinguals also require an effective and fast neural control system to allow them to select and control their languages even while code-switching rapidly.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] There is also evidence that suggests that the age at which an individual acquires a second language may play a significant role in the varying brain functions associated with bilingualism.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] For example, individuals who acquired their second language early (before the age of 10) tend to have drastically different activation patterns than do late learners.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] However, late learners who achieve full proficiency in their second language tend to show similar patterns of activation during auditory tasks regardless of which language is being used, whereas early learners tend to activate different brain areas depending upon which language is being used.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Along with the neuroprotective benefits that help to prevent onset of age-related cognitive issues such as dementia, bimodal bilinguals also experience a slightly different pattern of organization of language in the brain.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] While hearing bimodal bilinguals showed less parietal activation than deaf signers when asked to use only sign language, those same bimodal bilinguals demonstrated greater left parietal activation than did monolinguals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Parietal activation is not typically associated with language production but rather with motor activity.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Therefore, it is logical that bimodal bilinguals, when switching between speech- and sign-based language, stimulate their left parietal areas as a result of their increased need to combine both motor action and language production.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Moreover, it has been proven that there is a parallel or simultaneous language activation during language use.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] This activation occurs when the bilingual uses language, regardless of the L1 or L2, being used.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The dominance or lack of dominance of a language does not impact the stimulation of the brain when a language is being used.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] This same activation happens with any language modality, meaning the brain is activated whether the language is written, signed, or spoken.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Bimodal bilinguals may identify with Deaf communities, hearing communities, or both, and language identity varies widely.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Some individuals emphasize proficiency in one language over the other, while others view both languages as integral to their communicative repertoire.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Identity positions are influenced by family background, education, access to peers, and sociocultural attitudes toward both signed and spoken languages.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] As is the case in many situations of oral-language bilingualism, bimodal bilingualism in the U.S. involves two languages with vastly different social status.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] ASL has traditionally not even had the status of being considered a legitimate language; as roughly 90% of deaf children are born to hearing parents being able to even begin learning sign is a privilege for many.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Hearing parents of deaf children have historically been advised not to allow their children to learn ASL, as they were informed it would prevent the acquisition of English.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Despite the fact that Deaf children's early exposure to ASL has now been shown to enhance their aptitude for acquiring English competency, the unequal social status of ASL and English, and of sign languages and oral languages, remains.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] For deaf children, subtractive models of bilingual education, combined with the lack of foundation of a native language, typically result in language deprivation and delay in cognitive development (source needed).
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Simultaneous communication, or SimCom, which is a method of signing that represents English in its structure and elements, typically following English word order but still using one sign per word.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] However, research has shown this method of communication is not ideal for bilingual language learning.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Methodologies, strategies and support in bimodal bilingual education, as well as the language background and linguistic capital of bimodal bilingual educators are key aspects to the achievements of language competence of bimodal bilingual learners.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The written forms of language can be considered another modality.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Sign languages do not have widely accepted written forms, so deaf individuals learn to read and write an oral language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Orthographic systems employ the morphology, syntax, lexical choices, and often phonetic representation of their target language in at least superficial ways; one must learn these new features of the target language in order to read or write.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In communities where there is standardized education for the deaf, such as the United States and the Netherlands, deaf individuals do gain skill sets in reading and writing in the oral language of the community.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In such a state, bilingualism is achieved between a sign language and the written form of the community's oral language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] In this view, all sign–print bilinguals are bimodal bilinguals, but all bimodal bilinguals may not be sign–print bilinguals.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Children who are deaf and employ a sign language as their primary language learn to read in slightly different ways than their hearing counterparts.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Much as speakers of oral languages most frequently achieve spoken fluency before they learn to read and write, the most successful profoundly deaf readers first learn to communicate in a sign language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Research suggests that there is a mapping process, in which features from the sign language are accessed as a basis for the written language, similar to the way hearing unimodal bilinguals access their primary language when communicating in their second language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Profoundly deaf ASL signers show that fluency in ASL is the best predictor of high reading skills in predicting proficiency in written English.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Highly proficient signing deaf children use more evaluative devices in writing than less proficient signers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Their relatively frequent omission of English articles may indicate a developmental stage in which the transfer effect—typically advantageous for reading—temporarily promotes interaction between the morphosyntactic systems of written English and ASL.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Deaf children then appear to map the new morphology, syntax, and lexical choices of their written language onto the existing structures of their primary sign language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The study examined deaf and hearing readers' reading processes and their responses to syntactic manipulations by using self-pacing methods.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The experiment included of animate and inanimate subjects, actives and passives, as well as subject and object relatives.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Hearing readers had higher comprehension accuracy than deaf readers, according to the findings of the study.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Deaf readers, on the other hand, can read and grasp sentences faster than hearing readers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] According to the study, self-pacing is a better method for deaf readers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] There are mixed results in how important phonological information is to deaf individuals when reading and when that information is obtained.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Alphabets, abugidas, abjads, and syllabaries all seem to require the reader/writer to know something about the phonology of their target language prior to learning the system.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Profoundly deaf children do not have access to the same auditory base that hearing children do.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Orally trained deaf children do not always use phonological information in reading tasks, word recognition tasks or homophonic tasks; however, deaf signers who are not orally trained do utilize phonological information in word-rhyming tasks.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Furthermore, when performing on tasks with phonologically confusable initial sounds, hearing readers made more errors than deaf readers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Yet when given sentences that are sub-lexically confusable when translated into ASL, deaf readers made more errors than hearing readers.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The conceptual boundary of what defines a bimodal bilingual might vary across studies.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Some researchers limit this to hearing individuals who know a signed and spoken language; others limit it to Deaf signers who acquire a spoken or written language.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] The impact of bimodal bilingualism on cognition (see section above) remains to be researched.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Not every result should be considered a fact.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Many of these results depend on individual language history, including which modality is dominant and how often they use it.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] Attitudes towards sign languages, language policy, and educational methods vary across communities, institutions, and state lines.
[src:bimodal-bilingualism/bimodal-bilingualism] These differences will influence both language access and identity.
